Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "NuGet slow (read: unusable) after migrating to PackageReference" (#7669) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
## Details about Problem
NuGet product used (NuGet.exe | VS UI | Package Manager Console | dotnet.exe): Visual Studio UI
NuGet version (x.x.x.xxx): 4.9 (?, whatever bundles with VS)
VS version (if appropriate): 15.9.4
OS version (i.e. win10 v1607 (14393.321)): Win7 7601

Worked before? If so, with which NuGet version: Pre VS 15.9.something and *definitely* pre-PackageReference

## Detailed repro steps so we can see the same problem

1. Going through our solution of ~200 projects.
2. Right click on each references node and switch to PackageReference. (this was slow, 30-40 seconds per project, but I figured it was a one time expense).
3. Attempt to do any sort of package management afterwards...and wait quite a long time.

Events.RelatedDescription: Closed issue "NuGet CLI restore multiple solutions at once" (#6397) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
## Details about Problem

I have a build where I need to restore packages for approximately 140 solutions, with each multiple projects. I am using the NuGet CLI tool to do so.

Restoring NuGetâ€™s when the cache is cleared takes around 18 minutes for these solutions and around 6 minutes when the cache contains all the packages.

I find that since I need to feed NuGet.exe with one solution at a time, the 6 minutes when cache contains all packages, is made up of the overhead it takes for NuGet.exe to initialize and not the restore command itself.
I can reduce the 6 minutes to around 30 seconds if I generate a solution file, with all the projects all the 140 or so solutions contain and restore packages against that generated solution file.

Would it be possible to have NuGet restore accept multiple sln or csproj files to restore packages for. Perhaps do something clever not to attempt to restore the same packages more than one time etc.

NuGet version 4.4.1.4656

## Detailed repro steps so we can see the same problem

1. Create a whole bunch of solutions with multiple projects each having NuGet dependencies

2. Restore using NuGet

Events.RelatedDescription: Opened issue "Populate Solution Explorer package/project transitive dependencies from assets file" (#9580) at NuGet/Home
Events.RelatedBody:
[Copied from https://dev.azure.com/devdiv/DevDiv/_workitems/edit/1107557]
For .NET Project System projects (eg. SDK style projects) where the Dependencies node exists, transitive dependencies of package and project references will no longer be populated using data from design time builds. Instead, this data will be lazily acquired from the assets file directly.

This code was originally going to exist in the Project System repo, but it requires logic from NuGet which is not consumable within VS due to problems with binding redirects.

## NuGet.org will temporarily remove support for TLS 1.0/1.1 on February 26, 2020

We plan to temporarily remove support for TLS 1.0/1.1 across 3 time slots in a 24 hour period, for 4 hours each, to ensure overlap with normal working hours across the globe. If you discover that you are impacted and cannot identify a workaround, please open an issue on the NuGet Gallery GitHub repo.

Read this blog post to learn more and to identify the test slot time in your time zone - https://devblogs.microsoft.com/nuget/deprecating-tls-1-0-and-1-1-on-nuget-org-stage-1/
